post_text: Over the summer months, the Performing Arts Center (PAC) entrance was temporarily used as the middle/high school entrance. The main Middle and High School entrances are up and running and can be used for building entry during the school day. The outer door to each vestibule is unlocked and the inner doors are locked within the vestibule. Office personnel provides access to the office area once you are inside the vestibule. The Performing Arts Center is no longer being utilized as an entrance.

Back to School Reminder #2 - Hand Washing & Lunch:
Hand sanitizer will be readily available throughout buildings at main entrances, commons area, and classrooms. PK-4th grade students will schedule hand-washing three-times a day. 5-8 students scheduled prior to lunch. Hand-washing will be supported throughout the day.

Lunch: Additional spacing will be created and more grade level separation. Buffet style meals will be limited, but choices will continue although served directly. Some food items may be limited. PARENTS/GUESTS WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO EAT LUNCH WITH STUDENTS UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE.

post_text: Back To School Reminder #1 - Temperature Checks: Parents are asked to screen your children. If your child has a temperature of 100.4 or greater they should be kept home. The school will be randomly conducting temperature checks once your child is at school. Random temperature checks will take place throughout the day. If your child is randomly selected and pre-screens for a temperature, a second screening will be conducted in the office. If a temperature is present, parents/guardians will be contacted to pick their child up from school. Students are not to return to school until they are fever free without medication for 24 hours. A consultation may take place between the Nurse and Local Health.

post_text:
We would like to wish the Class of 2020 the best of luck in their future endeavors. We are happy that we were able to provide them with a memorable graduation ceremony last evening.

Unfortunately, we will be cancelling all intentions to hold Prom this summer. We do this with a very heavy heart and we are very disappointed. Students have sacrificed and continue to sacrifice a great deal during this time. As our Health District enters Phase III today, guidelines state no parades, carnivals, or dances. Dances are permissible at events, but individuals must remain at their tables/seats and keep social distancing between groups. Those guidelines make it very difficult to host a high school prom and we apologize.

With last evening's Graduation Ceremony, the 2019-2020 school year is officially over! We are looking forward to a normal 2020-2021 school year. We hope that no student will miss out on any future academic time or activities throughout the next school year and we will continue to fight for their opportunity to participate in all that they deserve. Thank you!

post_text: Today marks 7 weeks until the start of the 2020-2021 School Year. Central City Public Schools is planning on starting on-time and in full-session. We have worked on making decisions two-weeks at a time throughout this entire situation. We are hopeful that by doing so we have made the best possible decisions. With that stated, to attempt to guess what restrictions, guidelines, or recommendations will exist, if any, by the start of school would be just that.....a guess that could lead to confusion. Over the next few weeks, we will continue to analyze and research this ever-changing situation. Again, Central City Public Schools plans to start school on-time and in full-session. If any restrictions, guidelines, or suggestions exist, we will provide additional information in the upcoming weeks with the intent to provide that information before the end of July. Thank you for your continued support. Our community has worked through this situation better than nearly any school district or community. We appreciate all that you continue to do for your children and community.

post_text: In a world of crazy and in a world in which you only hear about the bad things it sure is great to know great things are taking place in small town USA. Patrick Jones of Lycos Construction provided a $100 check today to our Give Back Fund out of his own pocket "because this school does a lot for the community and it is obvious you guys love kids." That is someone from the outside watching what we do here at Central City. In addition, Tri-Cities Roofing and other companies that have been working here have provided nearly $1500 in Bison Bucks to be utilized in our local community and to help our businesses. In a world of ugly, spread the good that happens EVERY DAY in small town USA.

post_text:
The District is currently making plans for on-site summer school to begin on June 8th. Additional information, regarding eligibility, times, and other items will be communicated through Building Principals. We are planning to begin summer school on June 8th and conclude June 26th. This will include elementary summer school for K-6 students and credit recovery for 7-12.

We are also planning to begin ESY services that will also begin June 8th. The Special Education Director will be contacting eligible families.

Driver's Education is tentatively planned to begin July 6th. Additional information will be provided in the future.

The Weight Room will be opening for weight training and conditioning on June 1st. Strength coaches have sent out information regarding dates, times, and guidelines. Students are to select a time slot and there will be no changes to groups once the program starts.

post_text: Seniors: This has been a very difficult finish to the school year and we appreciate your efforts. Senior learning curriculum will officially end next Friday, May 1st, 2020. Many of you have done a great job completing requirements and have one week to finish your course work. Office staff will be getting a hold of you during the week of May 4th to make arrangements for certain items. Some seniors have additional requirements that will need to be completed in a timely fashion. We look forward to helping you finish your requirements. More information will be provided in the near future and we look forward to the July 5th commencement ceremony.

post_text: Construction Update (4-17-2020): Considerable amount of progress this week. Inside flooring has been removed and floors have been prepped. A considerable amount of demolition took place in the existing Industrial Technology area and the addition is ready for paint. The science wing is ready to be framed as rough-ins have been completed. The new office area is ready for sheetrock and the commons area is about to be opened up. The next two weeks will continue to show visible progress.

post_text:
Tonight at 8:20 pm, Central City Public Schools will join the national “Be the Light” campaign, and will turn on the stadium lights at the Preferred Popcorn Field. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes, honoring the Class of 2020.

Please feel free to drive by, observe and honk your horn for the Class of 2020! Please do not stop or get out of your vehicle, in order to follow the Central Nebraska Health Department and the Governor’s guidelines for social distancing and grouping.

Even if you cannot make it to the stadium, turn on your house lights at 8:20 pm in recognition of the Class of 2020.

We will NOT be delivering educational materials or meals during that four-day stretch.

Today's meal service will include Todays's lunch and Friday's breakfast. Also included, today, will be a sack lunch for Friday and breakfast for Saturday. There will be no lunch service on Monday, April 13th.

Deliveries and pick-up will not take place on Friday, April 10th or Monday, April 13th. The deliveries typically scheduled for Mondays, will simply move to Tuesday the 14th.

Thank you and have a great weekend.

Beginning tomorrow (Tuesday, March 31st), we are going to adjust our lunch pick-up time at North Park. Pick-up time will now be from 11am until Noon five days a week. The other two pick-up locations will remain 11am-12:30pm.

post_text: Thank you for your continued support. We have now completed nearly three days of deliveries. With anything new, there are always issues to work through. We ask that students/parents communicate with their teachers and building administrators to ensure that you are receiving what you need. As deliveries continue, we will state that the safety and well-being of our staff is of the upmost importance. We have had numerous situations and concerns with dogs and other risks. In the event that there are concerns with a drop-off location, our delivery personnel have been advised to not stop. Please do your part to ensure their safety, knowing that deliveries will take place between 10am and 2pm. In addition, there is always the risk of rain. Families may want to place a cooler or tote at the door to prepare for rain. Again, please communicate with our staff as we continue to work through this process.

post_text:
From the Central City Public School Board of Education:

The Central City Board of Education would like to take this time to say thank you to all of our incredible administration, certified, & classified staff. We realize this isn’t the job anyone signed up for. We also realize what a fantastic job everyone has done when you were asked to step up on a moments notice to change absolutely everything you do to service all students in our district. Without each one of you doing your part, this wouldn’t be possible! Our thanks seems so minimal at this time, but we see what a huge role each & every one of you are, to making Bison Nation a success! During these unprecedented times, we may not know what our new normal looks like, but we know we wouldn’t want to navigate it with any other team! Without a doubt, we know Bison Nation will survive this unusual time by working & learning together along the way! Thank you for your courage & strength in your leadership & for always doing it for the betterment of all students in the Central City School District! Keep up the great work! GO BISON!

post_text: Central City Public School staff members have diligently worked to provide alternative educational opportunities to our students as we navigate through this extremely difficult time. Current guidance is that we remain closed until April 30th, but to continue to re-assess the situation. Under the two-week premises of assessment, we will continue to evaluate the situation and we will be prepared to open sooner, if deemed safe to do so. However, we all must be prepared for the reality that we may not re-open the schoolhouse doors this school year. At this time, we will remain closed until at least April 14th. We remain committed to our students, supporting them, and providing them with the many valuable experiences they deserve. We hope that everyone can remain supportive throughout this situation. Please continue to communicate with your teachers and building administrators as we proceed through the provided alternative educational materials. As a school district, we can only apologize for the current situation and remain hopeful to see our awesome students soon.

post_text: We are planning on serving over 220 free meals tomorrow and moving forward to District students. This meal includes lunch for the day and breakfast for the next day. Pick-up sites are located at the following spots: Middle School 5/6 Hallway 11am - 12:30pm, Elementary East Entrance 11am - 12:30pm, and North Park from 11:30am - 12:30pm. In addition, we are delivering sack lunches to those outside of the pick-up areas. If you would like to take part in this program, please email Amber Johnson @ ajohnson@centralcityps.org so that we can plan a reasonable count.

post_text: Beginning on Wednesday, March 25th, Central City Public Schools will begin to provide eLearning and alternative learning opportunities to our students. 7-12 students will be conducting all eLearning and students have their Chromebooks. We have arranged Internet services or alternatives for those students. PK through sixth grade students will be conducting a mixture of eLearning and alternative learning opportunities and we have arranged for devices, Internet services or alternatives for those students. Students and parents will be receiving additional information from their teachers and building administrators. We will be providing delivery and pick-up services to your door step beginning next Tuesday and during this time. Thank you and please help us support the education of your child during this time.

post_text:
Due to the recent weather and the use of snow days, we will be making the following modifications to our calendar.

Monday, February 10th will now be a Full Day of school
with NO in-service.
Thursday, April 9th will now be a Full Day of school
prior to Spring Break.

In the event we have a fifth “Snow Day,” Thursday, March
5th will become a Full Day and we WILL have school with
a 1:30pm dismissal on Friday, March 6th.

In the event we have a sixth “Snow Day,” or it occurs after
March 6th, we will move the last day of school to
Thursday, May 21st.

In the event we have a seventh, “Snow Day,” our last day of
school will be Friday, May 22nd.

Thank you,

post_text: Attention CCHS College-bound Seniors – The Merrick Foundation Scholarship Application deadline is on February 1st. All college-bound seniors from CCHS should apply! Please complete all of the parts needed for the application. If you plan to apply for any scholarship with an * because you have a financial need, you will need to submit information from your completed FAFSA. Make sure that you ask adults who know you well and who are not related to you to complete recommendation forms. The recommendation forms can be found on the Merrick Foundation website, under Scholarship Submissions. Counselor Anderson will submit high school transcripts for all seniors who apply. The deadline to apply is February 1st.

The deadline to apply is February 1st.

post_text: Did you know that you can donate and support Central City Public Schools through the Merrick Foundation? Your donation will help current and future students continue to learn and grow in an encouraging environment. You have the ability to indicate which program you would like your donation to go to. Various accounts have been established to support our students (Science, Industrial Technology/Agriculture, General Academics, Fine Arts, and Athletics). For more information, please visit https://www.merrick-foundation.org/ways-to-give/centalcitypublicschools.html.

post_text: Friday, January 17th was our last snow day. In the event that weather happens in the future and school is cancelled, please be prepared that we may have to adjust our calendar. We all like a snow day, but please hope for sunny and warm weather until the conclusion of the school year.

post_text: Phase II construction is scheduled to begin on Monday! This is a very exciting time, but it will be very hectic over the next few months. Our goal is to minimally disrupt the normal school day throughout this process. However, our goal is also to complete construction prior to the 2020-2021 school year beginning. This week and into early next week, Boyd Jones and our District will be working on scheduling details and working to establish work zones. As these final details are finalized, we will inform those impacted and share that schedule with patrons. Stay tuned as we get set to begin!
text: Phase II construction is scheduled to begin on Monday! This is a very exciting time, but it will be very hectic over the next few months. Our goal is to minimally disrupt the normal school day throughout this process. However, our goal is also to complete construction prior to the 2020-2021 school year beginning. This week and into early next week, Boyd Jones and our District will be working on scheduling details and working to establish work zones. As these final details are finalized, we will inform those impacted and share that schedule with patrons. Stay tuned as we get set to begin!

post_text:
Our Student of the Month program recognizes two students in each building (six total each month) for their character, dedication, and commitment to their school and academic well-being. In the past, businesses would sponsor one or two months and provide a prize to each student for that month (6) with a value of $5-10. This tended to be a gift or gift card of some type.

We normally send this request out via the Chamber, but they do not have a Director at this time. Please let us know if you would be interested in supporting this program! Please contact jjensen@centralcityps.org if you are interested. THANK YOU FOR YOUR SUPPORT!

post_text: Elementary News: As school starts on Thursday, construction will continue at the Elementary Building. Construction crews will be completing work in the new elementary offices (previous Central Office) over the next two weeks. Students are asked to enter at the main/center entrances of the building during the month of August and a temporary elementary office has been established up the stairs in the 1927 building. This construction will be for only a short time and the construction will not impact the school day of our elementary students.

post_text: Construction Update (July 4th, 2019): High School Special Education area has been framed. Galusha Electric and McLlnay Plumbing were in right behind the framers. Sheetrock will start in this area Friday. Between the Special Education and Alternative Education renovations, CCPS will reduce contractural services by nearly $300,000 and provide services in our community, starting this upcoming school year. The new preschool classroom has been framed and ready for sheetrock Friday. Framing is taking place today and through the weekend in the new elementary office location.

Central City High School Activities
May 13, 2019 at 8:33 AM ·

Youth Football Sign-Ups:
Central City's youth football program is played through the Columbus Area Youth Football Organization. This program is for kids (entering in the fall) 3rd and 4th (flag football) and 5th and 6th (tackle football)
Sign ups will be held on the following dates:
May 14th - 5:30 to After 5th/6th Honors Night
May 15th - 5:30 to 7:00
*Registration will be held in the Middle School Commons area
*3rd/4th Grade is $80
*5th/6th Grade is $100

Many of you have completed pre-registration documents, but this will be actual sign-ups. As in past years, you will have the opportunity to cover registration fees with raffle tickets provided later.
